The essential elements of a trespass are:

    1. A person without legal right;
    2. Action constituting an invasion of another’s possessory rights;
    3. Damages resulting from such invasion.

To prove liability, a plaintiff must establish four things: (1) defendant wrongfully entered onto the property; (2) entry was made for the purpose of causing harm; (3) actual damages; and (4) reasonable expenses related to the repair or replacement of damaged property. 

It sounds like your client might potentially have a claim for trespass based on allegations that you've provided above. To determine whether you're likely to prevail on this claim, you'll need to carefully review the facts of the case and consult with an attorney specializing in tort law. Good luck!
